The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New York, Aug. 11: Former WorldCom finance chief Scott Sullivan was sentenced to five years in prison today for his high-ranking role in the largest accounting fraud in US history. Sullivan became the fifth WorldCom executive to be sentenced to prison in the $11-billion scandal. His sentence is topped only by that of ex-CEO Bernard Ebbers, who got 25 years. Sullivan, 43, was the star witness at Ebbers?s trial earlier this year. 

 London, Aug. 11: Lakshmi Mittal, owner of Mittal Steel Co, the world?s largest steelmaker, may dilute his 88 per cent stake in the company through acquisitions rather than issuing new shares, spokeswoman Nicola Davidson said.

 New Delhi, Aug. 11: The empowered committee of state finance ministers will meet on August 24 to discuss post-VAT implementation issues, including the uniform floor rate of tax on bullion, said committee secretary Ramesh Chandra.

 New Delhi, Aug. 11: The CBI has raided some of the offices of Volkswagen. A CBI spokesman said sleuths were conducting searches at the residence of Volkswagen chief in India, Ashok Jain, in Agra today.

 Mumbai, Aug. 11: The Centre for Monitoring Indian Economy (CMIE) today revised upwards its forecast for industrial growth this fiscal to 7.65 per cent from the earlier projection of 7.5 per cent.




